1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,720
Hello everyone, my name is Ian Barash, my project is the Multi-Signature Authentication

2
00:00:07,720 --> 00:00:08,720
Web Proxy.

3
00:00:08,720 --> 00:00:12,560
Today I'll be talking about how I spent a week researching cryptography and then threw

4
00:00:12,560 --> 00:00:15,160
half of it away.

5
00:00:15,160 --> 00:00:18,080
So my idea, it seemed perfect at the start.

6
00:00:18,080 --> 00:00:23,840
I was going to use threshold signature cryptography, which requires several people to approve before

7
00:00:23,840 --> 00:00:25,120
a sensitive action runs.

8
00:00:25,120 --> 00:00:29,600
The same guarantees that protect crypto wallets.

9
00:00:29,600 --> 00:00:40,200
So I went and I researched four of these schemes, Frost, Moosig2, GG20, and DKLS.

10
00:00:40,200 --> 00:00:46,520
In these schemes, each approver holds a key and then their shares combine into one signature.

11
00:00:46,520 --> 00:00:50,960
This means that no approver ever needs to trust the server with their secret.

12
00:00:50,960 --> 00:00:56,180
This is cutting edge cryptography, it's very mathematically elegant and exactly what the

13
00:00:56,180 --> 00:00:58,520
crypto world uses.

14
00:00:58,520 --> 00:01:03,680
But it just didn't really fit with my project.

15
00:01:03,680 --> 00:01:07,800
For one, every approver now becomes a key manager.

16
00:01:07,800 --> 00:01:10,120
If you lose a key, the server can't help you.

17
00:01:10,120 --> 00:01:19,200
And for approvers that are not technically savvy, that's not really what I wanted.

18
00:01:19,200 --> 00:01:22,720
Second, the parties have to talk to each other.

19
00:01:22,720 --> 00:01:28,720
They have to actually do the cryptography with themselves rather than with the server.

20
00:01:28,720 --> 00:01:37,360
And when approvals can be hours apart, that didn't really seem very usable in my project

21
00:01:37,360 --> 00:01:39,000
scope.

22
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:41,720
And three, the security still rests on the server.

23
00:01:41,720 --> 00:01:46,760
There still needs to be code that's running on a server that the approvers will need to

24
00:01:46,760 --> 00:01:48,400
trust.

25
00:01:48,400 --> 00:01:56,720
And so even though you take away... if you compromise a key, it's basically the same

26
00:01:56,720 --> 00:01:59,480
as compromising a password.

27
00:01:59,480 --> 00:02:01,440
So that's what I decided to do.

28
00:02:01,440 --> 00:02:07,080
Instead of doing the threshold cryptography, I did a credential-backed approval, where

29
00:02:07,080 --> 00:02:10,520
approvers can sign in with a password and a one-time code.

30
00:02:10,520 --> 00:02:14,040
And then each approval is cryptography tied to that login.

31
00:02:14,040 --> 00:02:16,400
It's signed and it's tampered effort.

32
00:02:16,400 --> 00:02:19,840
It's much simpler for people and it is strong where it counts.

33
00:02:19,840 --> 00:02:26,880
So I wrote this up into an architecture design record, my first actually.

34
00:02:26,880 --> 00:02:32,440
And really, I attribute this change to being so cheap because I did it on paper rather

35
00:02:32,440 --> 00:02:39,080
than when I had a full code base that I would have to change.

36
00:02:39,080 --> 00:02:41,620
So how does the flow actually work?

37
00:02:41,620 --> 00:02:44,200
You can see it here.

38
00:02:44,200 --> 00:02:49,760
The proxy requester will make HTTP requests to the proxies.

39
00:02:49,760 --> 00:02:55,560
The proxy will store some artifacts and notify the approvers.

40
00:02:55,560 --> 00:03:04,780
Once everything is approved, an executor will grab it, read the artifact, and then actually

41
00:03:04,780 --> 00:03:09,480
publish it to the package repository.

42
00:03:09,480 --> 00:03:18,120
And that is brought all the way back to the requester in an email link.

43
00:03:18,120 --> 00:03:20,080
And the rest of the system is specified too.

44
00:03:20,080 --> 00:03:27,920
So over the past two weeks, I, with some AI help, have written about 5,800 lines of code

45
00:03:27,920 --> 00:03:35,000
over 32 commits, which are all specification, no actual application code yet.

46
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:40,920
And it really defines what the system is made of and how it'll talk together, every state

47
00:03:40,920 --> 00:03:45,480
that a request can move through, the exact cryptography down to even the parameters that

48
00:03:45,480 --> 00:03:53,920
I'll be using, a threat model, who uses it and why, that's all documented in the PRD,

49
00:03:53,920 --> 00:04:02,160
as well as shared account access, self-service portals, and second factor logins.

50
00:04:02,160 --> 00:04:08,080
Second factor access being the other use case that I am putting aside for now.

51
00:04:08,080 --> 00:04:12,120
And then I ran a consistency audit to make sure that none of the documentation conflicted

52
00:04:12,120 --> 00:04:13,780
with each other.

53
00:04:13,780 --> 00:04:18,920
This really was to ensure that I was really going deep on the parts that actually mattered

54
00:04:18,920 --> 00:04:27,300
rather than trying to describe a whole bunch of features and only half filled them out.

55
00:04:27,300 --> 00:04:32,840
And so this is where I want your approval and your feedback.

56
00:04:32,840 --> 00:04:39,880
So I built the flow that you saw in the previous slide for package publishing.

57
00:04:39,880 --> 00:04:49,480
However, shared accounts, which is the second use case, login or user portals and second

58
00:04:49,480 --> 00:04:55,400
factor logins, I'm really putting aside for only if time allows.

59
00:04:55,400 --> 00:05:01,220
So I want to ask you, is this the first right place to build or have I over-scooped or under-scooped

60
00:05:01,220 --> 00:05:02,220
DNDT?

